commentBody:
@Terry AVL NC

Yep.  Flyspecking seemed to take as much time as the puzzle.

Most of the "solving" was just a speed typing test.  I suppose that's what caused all the typos.

@sotto voce,

Your comment reminds me of the old saying,

“Behind every successful man, there stands a totally surprised woman.”

@NYC Traveler

Didn't know that one.
Brilliant! Lol

@NYC Traveler
My favourite along those lines is attributed to Charlotte Whitton, former mayor of Ottawa decades ago. 
"To succeed, a woman has to be twice as good as a man. Fortunately, it's not difficult."

@Paul
On a recent vacation to Yellowstone, a young Aussie woman was part of our 6-day tour group. Very fascinating and intelligent woman. She's an Astrophysicist and knows all about parsecs, novas, etc. No one used G'day to her, just once or twice. She educated a few of us on prawns though, not shrimp.

The funniest moment was when one of the guides pulled out a pocket knife to cut the tag off a piece of luggage. I said to her "He called that a knife." Right on cue, she came back with "That's not a knife." Fortunately she didn't produce a Dundee knife.

@Jill
Are you sure? I have heard--I think from linguist McWhorter-- of "all y'all" being the term for more than one while "y'all" is used for one. That was in a discussion of the evolution of "you" from plural to either.
  But perhaps a regional difference?

@Red Carpet

Two to one in favor of a blizzard.

Thus are the ballots counted and confirmed.

@Francis
3 to 1!

It was +15C here this weekend. Creepy. And the drainage systems are struggling to cope with the massive melts from this very snowy winter.

@SBK

I think it's officially 3:2, since apparently we're keeping count and what-not. 

I can live with some snow but a blizzard!? Thanks, no. I'll take safety and passable roads any day!

@Jane Wheelaghan

I did miss a few as well. OCONNOR was gained entirely from crossings, as was ICE, but then I couldn’t name any Supreme Court justice man or woman, and my knowledge of rap, Grammy winning or otherwise is limited. 

Hermione Granger was of course created by JK Rowling, who is estimated to be the 7th best selling author ever on Wikipedia. In fact they have women as 7 of the top 10. Seemed like a good stat for today!

@Chris
There was a lot of French! That was good for me, because they were all gimmes. Not gloating, I swear.

The drag show items are almost always the BOAS. But yeah, bras have funny clues, too.

@Matt

Misandrist?  You *do* realize that there are many wonderful men out there don't you?  If not, you're keeping company with the wrong crowd.

I agree with you on the cluing today.  A big Monday grid is a little tedious.

@Matt

Wow, that has not been my experience, and I'm sorry it has been yours. 

I know people who are those things and worse.  I just haven't seen a gender component to it.

@dutchiris
Surely the close should be:

But now rejoice: it's Women's Day.

@SBK
After I had already hit the button and it was too late, I wanted to have said:

But now behold, it's Women's Day!

@Pat
Good call. I knew of the other spelling, but didn't realize it was exclusively a metal framework. 
<a href="https://www.thefreedictionary.com/grill" target="_blank">https://www.thefreedictionary.com/grill</a>

@Andrzej

Wow!  That's really impressive!  Especially for that array of cities.

The pictures in the article were gorgeous.

@Francis

There's more where that pic came from:

<a href="https://go2warsaw.pl/en/main-page" target="_blank">https://go2warsaw.pl/en/main-page</a>/

@Xword Junkie

I liked it better than you and found it an impressive way to celebrate the day, but some of the fill was quite questionable, and most of that can't be blamed on the theme.

SAY TO felt especially dubious to my ear.

@Xword Junkie
I had KIOWA for EVER! "WA" being the only fill-in had me fooled. I kept thinking along the lines of Army helicopter names in line with Native American tribes.
Then, I switched to OTAWA, and finally succumbed to ODAWA.

@mikeweb

It’s fascinating to see a couple people make this same “correction”, when the clue is perfectly fine as-is.

Bits and bytes are as interchangeable as gallons and quarts, regardless of how they may *tend* to be used.

@ColeenJ
I hope you realise you've already done 'a month of Sundays'!
Congratulations.

@Jill

I think you missed LW's point.  As they said, all the names were known and it was a PB time.

No learning necessary but lacking a wordplay challenge.

@Mean Old Lady

I take issue with your comparison. Dukes of Hazzard was a platform for Catherine Bach, a brunette with a famous but.

Today of all days, please objectify women accurately.

@Josh
I'm always late on weekends because of the sabbath, which gives me offline time Friday night and Saturday. With the early releases of puzzles those days, I'm always turning up when the posts have accumulated by the hundreds!
In the result, I'm often adding comments (and worse, queries) long after the party's over.

@Lisa Cummings

I don't know if I've made up the phrase myself or if another commenter has previously used it.
What is true and real, and that matters most, is that comments do get filtered electronically, so if one doesn't immediately get posted to the forum, chances are the EMUs didn't approve of something. Hence, decoys are needed.

@Debra King

It seems to me that you yourself are not being helpful of the cause you claim to support when you deny a woman constructor the respect, acknowledgement, and gratitude she so richly deserves.

As a woman, I know who I would be shaming if I were you and took the time to consider the absurdity of my post.

@Debra King

There's a thing called Poe's Law where any sufficiently outrageous parody is still indistinguishable from a sincerely expressed thought.

For your own sake I choose to believe that you were joking here.

@Barry Ancona
It’s a male rock band, so (that I have never heard), so I guess so. Interesting that both are near MEN ON base, though DOTTIE is nearby to counterbalance the baseball. 

I know nothing about puzzle construction. Do it work in such a way that you can get boxed into a corner— in this case the southwest— and have to make compromises with the fill?

@Jerry

I'm really sorry your parental situation was not ideal.

My parents, especially my mother, has been a genuine source of strength for me for decades, and I don't know what I would have done without her.

@Jerry The server at the Ethiopian restaurant where I had lunch today told me “Happy Women’s Day”. He prefaced it that “in his country” (I assume Ethiopia) it was women’s day & today he wasn’t sure if it was true here in the US. I assured him it was International Women’s Day. It was definitely the first time I can remember someone mentioning it out of the blue like that. This was also the first year that some of the hidden object games I play on my iPad mentioned it. I’m not sure what’s changed that it’s getting more attention. 

It’s not something I have marked on my calendar, but it’s one of those dates I definitely have in the back of my mind. 

My mother is currently visiting my brother in Poland & apparently there people give flowers to the women in their lives.

@Francis
@KB
It's all good. We're all shaped by circumstances beyond our control, be they positive or not so positive. I have the most respect for my wife, daughters, daughters-in-law, my Dutch grandmother, and the inventors, authors and innovators mentioned here. Not the movie stars or singers. I do admire women athletes over men, for some strange reason.

I'm glad for a day to recognize great people, women especially.
It's not all about me, I'll back out now.
Thanks, you two!
